body:
I think my contribution to those classes was when I tidied up the prediction intervals API, so I only have one very specific perspective on this. That said, I felt very much the same as you at the time I worked on it - I was unsure what the justification was for two separate classes (there was probably a good reason at the time, but it seems less clear now). It was difficult to figure out where new methods should live.

Something I liked in earlier versions of sktime that perhaps we could return to in this refactor is a simplification of the docstrings. At the moment, the documentation is spread across both private and public methods. Not only does this clutter up the codebase a little (and make it less readable), but it doesn't play as nicely with documentation tools like sphinx. I think it could be better to keep all of the meaningful user-focussed documentation in the public methods, and the private methods can contain very light documentation notes for developers (if absolutely necessary), or be undocumented (comments where they are called in the public methods can explain what they are being used for if needed). For example:

```python
def predict(self, fh, X=None, return_pred_int=False, alpha=DEFAULT_ALPHA):
    """Meaningful, generic, napoleon-formatted user documentation."""
    # Call class-specific implementation.
    return self._predict(fh=fh, X=X, return_pred_int=return_pred_int, alpha=alpha)

@abstractmethod
def _predict(self, fh, X=None, return_pred_int=False, alpha=DEFAULT_ALPHA):
    "A light, informal note *iff* it's useful for developers."
    raise NotImplementedError()
```
